Alone in a bathroom stall at 17, I received news that would forever change my life: I was going to be a single parent. 

As I held my baby in my arms for the first time, little did I anticipate the challenges that awaited us. Days turned into weeks, and my precious boy found himself in the ICU battling a brain bleed from our traumatic birth. 

His health improved and yet nothing got easier and that was the theme of my 20s. 

Life threw it’s curveballs, and I even caught a few but - I faced the harsh reality of eviction not just once, but multiple times. 

I vividly remember the day the bank I worked at - took away the very home I had purchased at the tender age of 22. 

How can they not pay me enough to support one child and the home they told me I could afford? I pleaded. 

It felt like a punch to the gut. 

But I refused to let it define me.

Today, as I reflect upon my journey, I am humbled and grateful. I stand as a testament to the resilience of a person who defied the odds. 

Against all challenges, I built a business from the ground up with no capital, experience or support and it has provided for us and allowed me to partially retire in my 30s, in my dream home that no one can ever take from me.
